[Surveillance of Legionnaires' disease (LD) in France started in 1987 with a mandatory clinician-based notification system http://www.q-net.net.au/~legion/Legionnaires_Disease_France.htm. France also participates in the European LD surveillance network (ELDSNet) related to travel-associated cases. _Legionella_ isolates have been routinely typed in France since 2008 by 3 methods: use of monoclonal antibodies, PFGE (pulsed-field gel electrophoresis), and amplification and sequencing of 7 selected genes to identify common-source outbreaks (sequencing can be done directly on pulmonary samples, even if no strain is isolated) to detect case clusters that have a common source and then identify their source of contamination (1).

1. Camp√®se C, Descours G, Lepoutre A, et al. Legionnaires' disease in France. Med Mal Infect. 2015;45(3):65-71. doi: 10.1016/j.medmal.2015.01.015. Abstract available at: http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25722040.

Montpellier, the 8th largest city in France, with a population of 268 456 in 2012, is the capital of the Occitanie region; it is located on the south coast of France on the Mediterranean Sea https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montpellier. Pictures of the apartment complex (La Nouvelle Vague) and a map showing its location can be found at http://www.supinvest.fr/programmes/p/residence-nouvelle-vague-palavas-flots-herault-pinel/. - Mod.ML

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4976135,58410.]
